SIMPLE: buccaneer
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Buccaneer
<hw>Buc`ca*neer"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>boucanier</ets>, fr. <ets>boucaner</ets> to smoke or broil meat and
fish, to hunt wild beasts for their skins, <ets>boucan</ets> a smoking
place for meat or fish, gridiron for smoking: a word of American
origin.]</ety> <def>A robber upon the sea; a pirate; -- a term applied
especially to the piratical adventurers who made depredations on the
Spaniards in America in the 17th and 18th centuries.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>bucanier</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Primarily, one who dries and smokes flesh or fish after
the manner of the Indians. The name was first given to the French
settlers in Haiti or Hispaniola, whose business was to hunt wild cattle
and swine.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Buccaneer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Buccaneer
<hw>Buc`ca*neer"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act the part of a
buccaneer; to live as a piratical adventurer or sea robber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Buccaneerish</ent>⟦br⟧
